article.headline: Creighton had won last five meetings
article.story: OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Nate Johnson made a running layup with 11 seconds left to give Nebraska a 71-70 victory Tuesday night over Creighton in the opening round of the NIT. Johnson's shot capped the Cornhuskers' comeback from a five-point deficit in the final two minutes. Nebraska (17-12) advances to play the winner of Wednesday's game between Troy State and Niagara. The game will be in Lincoln on Friday. Jake Muhleisen led the Huskers with 17 points and Johnson added 11 points. Creighton (20-9) got 16 points from Joe Dabbert, 15 from Johnny Mathies and 13 from Nate Funk. The Bluejays led 68-63, but Johnson trimmed the lead to 68-65 with 1:41 left. Johnson stole the ball after Dabbert made a bad pass on Creighton's ensuing possession, and John Turek hit a short shot to pull the Huskers to 68-67. Mathies' two free throws gave the Bluejays a three-point lead, but Turek came right back to dunk Muhleisen's miss. That gave Huskers a 70-69 lead with 42 seconds left. The Bluejays lost the ball after Mathies missed a desperation jumper as the shot clock expired, giving Nebraska possession with 22 seconds to play. Johnson brought the ball down the floor and banked in the winning shot. The Bluejays were slow to bring the ball up the court on their final possession, and Funk was well short with a final shot from the top of the key. Creighton had won the regular-season meeting between the teams 61-54 on Dec. 10.
